all properties needs be initialized in Swift if you does not using the unwrapper symbol &#39;?&#39; or &#39;!&#39; and you property needs be a type, for example:

    class ViewController: UIViewController {
        var numberOnScreen: 0
    }

it yet is wrong way to set the type, the number zero is a int, but when you use &#39;:&#39; the compiler is waiting the type, not the value, to fix that, you need to set first it type:

    class ViewController: UIViewController {
        var numberOnScreen: Int = 0
    }

that way above inicialized the ViewController with numbeROnScreen aways with zero, but if yout need to pass the value on a constructor you must to do:

    class ViewController: UIViewController {
        var numberOnScreen: Int
    
        init(newValue: Int) {
            self.numberOnScreen = newValue
            super.init(nibName: &quot;ViewController&quot;, bundle: nil)
        }
    
        required init?(coder aDecoder: NSCoder) {
            fatalError(&quot;init(coder:) has not been implemented&quot;)
        }
    }

Or if you want pass the value of numberOnScreen after initialize the ViewController, you must add the icon &#39;?&#39; to tell to ViewController that property going to be inicialize after initialized:


    class ViewController: UIViewController {
        var numberOnScreen: Int?
    }

But you need to be care to use that property above, it can be null, and to user it you need to use the unwrapper &#39;!&#39;, but the right way to access that value is using if let or guard 

    class Calculator {
    
        init() {
            let controller = ViewController()
            controller.numberOnScreen = 1
            guard let numberOfScreen = controller.numberOnScreen else {
                return
            }
            print(numberOfScreen)
        }
    
    }

