You can do in-place merge in linear time given that insert operation is O(1), which is typically true for all list implementations.

There is not much difference with your solution. The algorithm is very similar:

Let&#39;s have the following notation: *smaller list* is the list that we do not mutate. *Larger list* is the list that we mutate by inserting elements from the smaller list.

 - Start with two iterators pointing to the beginning of each list
 - If values at both iterators are the same, increment iterator of the smaller list (skip duplicates)
 - If the value at iterator of the larger list is greater (or we reached the end of the larger list), then insert the value from the smaller list before it, increment iterator of the smaller list
 - Otherwise, increment iterator of the larger list.
 - Terminate loop if iterator of the smaller list reached the end.

The code is below:

    #include &lt;list&gt;
    
    template&lt;typename T&gt;
    void mergeNoDups(std::list&lt;T&gt;&amp; larger, const std::list&lt;T&gt;&amp; smaller)
    {
    	typename std::list&lt;T&gt;::iterator itl = larger.begin();
    	typename std::list&lt;T&gt;::const_iterator its = smaller.begin();
    
        while (its != smaller.end())
        {
        	if (itl == larger.end() || *itl &gt; *its)
            {
        		larger.insert(itl, *its);
                ++its;
            }
        	else if (*itl == *its)
            {
                ++its;
            }
        	else // *itl &lt; *its
            {
        		++itl;
            }
        }
    }

